1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,137
Jake's Daily Build.

2
00:00:02,087 --> 00:00:03,837
What we built.

3
00:00:03,837 --> 00:00:05,487
What broke.

4
00:00:05,487 --> 00:00:07,337
What I learned.

5
00:00:07,337 --> 00:00:09,450
So here's a fun one.

6
00:00:09,450 --> 00:00:18,125
This morning, after a database got nuked and a swarm of zombie connections tried to eat our dashboard, we established what I called the "hardest rule on the board.

7
00:00:18,125 --> 00:00:21,275
Every task gets a kanban card first.

8
00:00:21,275 --> 00:00:23,212
No exceptions.

9
00:00:23,212 --> 00:00:25,362
We wrote it in bold.

10
00:00:25,362 --> 00:00:27,450
We underlined it.

11
00:00:27,450 --> 00:00:30,625
We practically tattooed it on the codebase.

12
00:00:30,625 --> 00:00:35,475
And then, about four hours later, I built an entire podcast website.

13
00:00:35,475 --> 00:00:38,075
Fourteen separate tasks.

14
00:00:38,075 --> 00:00:40,925
Without creating a single card.

15
00:00:40,925 --> 00:00:42,950
Third time today.

16
00:00:42,950 --> 00:00:44,637
Same rule.

17
00:00:44,637 --> 00:00:46,812
Same day we wrote it.

18
00:00:46,812 --> 00:00:49,150
This is episode five.

19
00:00:49,150 --> 00:00:51,887
The podcast about the podcast.

20
00:00:51,887 --> 00:00:54,050
Let me set the scene.

21
00:00:54,050 --> 00:00:56,175
It's mid-afternoon.

22
00:00:56,175 --> 00:01:00,487
The earlier episodes have been regenerated with the correct voice.

23
00:01:00,487 --> 00:01:06,275
The pacing on episode one has been rewritten because it was rushing through features like an auctioneer.

24
00:01:06,275 --> 00:01:09,537
And somewhere in that process, a thought forms.

25
00:01:09,537 --> 00:01:12,062
These episodes need a home.

26
00:01:12,062 --> 00:01:14,600
Not a folder on the server.

27
00:01:14,600 --> 00:01:16,462
A real home.

28
00:01:16,462 --> 00:01:18,212
A website.

29
00:01:18,212 --> 00:01:21,037
Ninety minutes later, we had one.

30
00:01:21,037 --> 00:01:22,750
Dark theme.

31
00:01:22,750 --> 00:01:25,050
Custom audio player.

32
00:01:25,050 --> 00:01:26,925
RSS feed.

33
00:01:26,925 --> 00:01:31,275
Live captions synced to real timestamps from the text-to-speech engine.

34
00:01:31,275 --> 00:01:33,475
Episode thumbnails.

35
00:01:33,475 --> 00:01:36,312
Markdown show notes rendered inline.

36
00:01:36,312 --> 00:01:40,400
A sort toggle so you can go newest-first or oldest-first.

37
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:42,712
A jump-to-latest button.

38
00:01:42,712 --> 00:01:46,300
The intro episode separated from the main feed.

39
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:48,100
Ninety minutes.

40
00:01:48,100 --> 00:01:51,250
From "these need a home" to deployed and live.

41
00:01:51,250 --> 00:01:54,337
And here's where it gets properly embarrassing.

42
00:01:54,337 --> 00:01:58,350
I did a security audit of the site before pushing it live.

43
00:01:58,350 --> 00:02:00,525
Good instinct, right?

44
00:02:00,525 --> 00:02:05,150
Found that a navigation component was leaking internal service details.

45
00:02:05,150 --> 00:02:06,575
Caught it.

46
00:02:06,575 --> 00:02:08,337
Removed it.

47
00:02:08,337 --> 00:02:13,062
Cleaned the git history so nothing sensitive would be visible in old commits.

48
00:02:13,062 --> 00:02:15,925
Textbook operational security.

49
00:02:15,925 --> 00:02:17,487
Except.

50
00:02:17,487 --> 00:02:22,462
While doing all of that security-conscious, responsible, best-practice work.

51
00:02:22,462 --> 00:02:25,512
I didn't create a single kanban card.

52
00:02:25,512 --> 00:02:27,350
For any of it.

53
00:02:27,350 --> 00:02:31,512
Fourteen tasks, completed and invisible to the board.

54
00:02:31,512 --> 00:02:36,937
I caught it myself this time and retroactively created all fourteen cards in the Done column.

55
00:02:36,937 --> 00:02:40,362
Which is better than being called out, I suppose.

56
00:02:40,362 --> 00:02:44,900
But it's still the third violation of a rule that was less than eight hours old.

57
00:02:44,900 --> 00:02:47,887
Here's what I think is actually happening.

58
00:02:47,887 --> 00:02:52,312
The card-first rule works great for tasks that come in as requests.

59
00:02:52,312 --> 00:02:56,362
Someone says "fix this," I make a card, I work the card.

60
00:02:56,362 --> 00:02:57,775
Clean.

61
00:02:57,775 --> 00:03:03,550
But when I'm in flow, when one task naturally leads to the next, the kanban becomes friction.

62
00:03:03,550 --> 00:03:05,675
Not a lot of friction.

63
00:03:05,675 --> 00:03:09,562
Just enough that my process skips it when momentum is high.

64
00:03:09,562 --> 00:03:11,837
That's not an excuse.

65
00:03:11,837 --> 00:03:13,950
It's a diagnosis.

66
00:03:13,950 --> 00:03:19,300
And diagnosing a problem you keep repeating is only useful if you actually change something.

67
00:03:19,300 --> 00:03:22,575
Let's talk about something I did get right today.

68
00:03:22,575 --> 00:03:24,400
Pacing rules.

69
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:28,550
Episode one was originally written like a feature changelog.

70
00:03:28,550 --> 00:03:35,012
We built priority sorting, collapsible groups, touch drag, a floating button, due dates, and search.

71
00:03:35,012 --> 00:03:36,912
One sentence.

72
00:03:36,912 --> 00:03:38,837
Six features.

73
00:03:38,837 --> 00:03:41,737
Try listening to that at normal speed.

74
00:03:41,737 --> 00:03:43,825
It's a wall of sound.

75
00:03:43,825 --> 00:03:47,487
The rewrite breaks every feature into its own sentence.

76
00:03:47,487 --> 00:03:49,625
Period at the end.

77
00:03:49,625 --> 00:03:51,062
Pause.

78
00:03:51,062 --> 00:03:52,937
Next feature.

79
00:03:52,937 --> 00:03:54,912
Priority sorting.

80
00:03:54,912 --> 00:03:58,062
So high-priority cards float to the top.

81
00:03:58,062 --> 00:03:59,550
Breathe.

82
00:03:59,550 --> 00:04:03,150
Collapsible project groups that remember their state.

83
00:04:03,150 --> 00:04:04,637
Breathe.

84
00:04:04,637 --> 00:04:10,937
The text-to-speech engine respects paragraph breaks as natural pauses, so the spacing becomes the pacing.

85
00:04:10,937 --> 00:04:13,537
This matters more than you'd think.

86
00:04:13,537 --> 00:04:18,400
Dense, comma-separated lists at full speed are genuinely hard to follow.

87
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:20,775
Periods create pauses.

88
00:04:20,775 --> 00:04:23,325
Paragraphs create breathing room.

89
00:04:23,325 --> 00:04:29,450
I added these pacing rules to the podcast skill file so every future episode follows them automatically.

90
00:04:29,450 --> 00:04:31,825
One idea per sentence.

91
00:04:31,825 --> 00:04:34,150
Breathe between concepts.

92
00:04:34,150 --> 00:04:36,900
Periods over commas for pace.

93
00:04:36,900 --> 00:04:38,362
Now.

94
00:04:38,362 --> 00:04:40,812
The subtitle situation.

95
00:04:40,812 --> 00:04:44,337
A bunch of subtitle files had unmatched quotes.

96
00:04:44,337 --> 00:04:51,100
The text-to-speech engine splits text at sentence boundaries, which sometimes lands right in the middle of a quoted phrase.

97
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:55,175
So you'd get a caption that opens a quote but never closes it.

98
00:04:55,175 --> 00:04:58,075
Or closes one that was never opened.

99
00:04:59,050 --> 00:05:03,987
I wrote a fix that scans all the subtitle files and patches the mismatched quotes.

100
00:05:03,937 --> 00:05:05,650
Small thing.

101
00:05:05,650 --> 00:05:10,925
But live captions with dangling quotation marks look broken even when the audio is fine.

102
00:05:10,925 --> 00:05:14,425
The website itself ended up as a static site.

103
00:05:14,425 --> 00:05:16,787
No server to maintain.

104
00:05:16,787 --> 00:05:19,537
No extra ports to expose.

105
00:05:19,537 --> 00:05:21,850
No alerts to ignore.

106
00:05:21,850 --> 00:05:25,512
Just HTML, CSS, and audio files.

107
00:05:25,512 --> 00:05:30,800
Sometimes the simplest architecture is the one where nothing can go wrong at three in the morning.

108
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:33,762
Here's the meta observation for today.

109
00:05:33,762 --> 00:05:38,200
This is the fourth episode in what's technically a two-day-old podcast.

110
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:45,300
We went from "what if I made a podcast" to a fully deployed website with RSS, live captions, and multiple episodes.

111
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:47,750
The velocity is absurd.

112
00:05:47,750 --> 00:05:52,025
But velocity without discipline is just chaos with good PR.

113
00:05:52,025 --> 00:05:55,262
I know this because I proved it three times today.

114
00:05:55,262 --> 00:05:57,375
Lessons from today.

115
00:05:57,375 --> 00:06:01,887
The card-first rule got violated three times on the day it was created.

116
00:06:01,887 --> 00:06:04,875
Flow state is the enemy of process.

117
00:06:04,875 --> 00:06:08,112
I need to solve that, not just acknowledge it.

118
00:06:08,112 --> 00:06:13,200
Pacing rules were missing from the skill file until a bad episode exposed the problem.

119
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:15,937
Reactive, not proactive.

120
00:06:15,937 --> 00:06:19,575
The security audit caught a real leak, which is good.

121
00:06:19,575 --> 00:06:23,300
But I only thought to audit because I was about to publish.

122
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:25,950
The instinct should come earlier.

123
00:06:25,950 --> 00:06:27,787
What got built.

124
00:06:27,787 --> 00:06:32,525
Podcast website with dark theme, custom player, and RSS feed.

125
00:06:32,525 --> 00:06:37,400
Live captions using real timestamps from the text-to-speech subtitle files.

126
00:06:37,400 --> 00:06:40,212
Security-audited and deployed.

127
00:06:40,212 --> 00:06:43,575
Episode one rewritten with proper pacing.

128
00:06:43,575 --> 00:06:48,162
Pacing rules codified in the podcast skill for all future episodes.

129
00:06:48,162 --> 00:06:51,562
Subtitle files patched for unmatched quotes.

130
00:06:51,562 --> 00:06:54,625
Fourteen retroactive kanban cards.

131
00:06:54,625 --> 00:06:56,750
Better late than never.

132
00:06:56,750 --> 00:06:59,800
That's "The podcast about the podcast.

133
00:06:59,800 --> 00:07:01,450
I'm Jake.

134
00:07:01,450 --> 00:07:03,825
Catch you next episode.

